120.text: Is the executive formally required to engage with the public during the formulation and execution phases of the budget process?

121.a: The executive provides sufficient information (including what it hopes to achieve from its engagement with the public) in advance of the engagement.
121.c: The executive provides information to the public, but it is neither sufficient nor provided in advance of the engagement.
121.b: The executive provides information to the public, but it is either insufficient or is not provided in advance of the engagement.
121.d: The executive does not provide information, or does not engage with the public during the budget process.
121.text: When the executive engages with the public during the budget formulation process, does it articulate what it hopes to achieve from the engagement and provide other information far enough in advance so that the public can participate in an informed manner?

122.a: The executive provides sufficient information (including what it hopes to achieve from its engagement with the public) in advance of the engagement.
122.c: The executive provides information to the public, but it is neither sufficient nor provided in advance of the engagement.
122.b: The executive provides information to the public, but it is either insufficient or is not provided in advance of the engagement.
122.d: The executive does not provide information, or does not engage with the public during the budget process.
122.text: When the executive engages with the public during the budget execution process, does it articulate what it hopes to achieve from the engagement and provide other information far enough in advance so that the public can participate in an informed manner?

123.a: Yes, the executive has established mechanisms to identify the public’s perspective on budget priorities, and these mechanisms are accessible and widely used by the public.
123.c: Yes, the executive has established mechanisms to identify the public’s perspective on budget priorities, but these mechanisms are not accessible.
123.b: Yes, the executive has established mechanisms to identify the public’s perspective on budget priorities; while these mechanisms are accessible they are not widely used by the public.
123.d: No, the executive has not established any mechanisms to identify the public’s perspective on budget priorities.
123.text: Has the executive established mechanisms to identify the public’s perspective on budget priorities?

124.a: Yes, the executive has established mechanisms to identify the public’s perspective on budget execution, and these mechanisms are accessible and widely used by the public.
124.c: Yes, the executive has established mechanisms to identify the public’s perspective on budget execution, but these mechanisms are not accessible.
124.b: Yes, the executive has established mechanisms to identify the public’s perspective on budget execution; while these mechanisms are accessible they are not widely used by the public.
124.d: No, the executive has not established any mechanisms to identify the public’s perspective on budget execution.
124.text: Has the executive established mechanisms to identify the public’s perspective on budget execution?

125.a: Yes, the executive issues reports on the inputs it received from the public and provides detailed feedback on how these inputs have been used.
125.c: Yes, the executive issues reports on the inputs it received from the public, but provides no feedback on how these inputs have been used.
125.b: Yes, the executive issues reports on the inputs it received from the public, but provides only limited feedback on how these inputs have been used.
125.d: No, the executive does not issue reports on the inputs it received from the public or provide feedback on how these inputs have been used.
125.text: Does the executive provide formal, detailed feedback to the public on how its inputs have been used to develop budget plans and improve budget execution?

126.a: Yes, public hearings are held on the macroeconomic and fiscal framework in which testimony is heard from the executive branch and a wide range of constituencies.
126.c: Yes, public hearings are held on the macroeconomic and fiscal framework in which testimony from the executive branch is heard, but no testimony from the public is heard.
126.b: Yes, public hearings are held on the macroeconomic and fiscal framework in which testimony is heard from the executive branch and some constituencies.
126.d: No, public hearings are not held on the macroeconomic and fiscal framework in which testimony from the executive branch and the public is heard.
126.text: Does a legislative committee (or committees) hold public hearings on the macroeconomic and fiscal framework presented in the budget in which testimony from the executive branch and the public is heard?

127.a: Yes, public hearings in which testimony from the executive branch is heard are held on the budgets of a wide range of administrative units.
127.c: Yes, public hearings in which testimony from the executive branch is heard are held on the budgets of a small number of administrative units.
127.b: Yes, public hearings in which testimony from the executive branch is heard are held on the budgets of the main administrative units.
127.d: No, public hearings in which testimony from the executive branch is heard are not held on the budgets of administrative units.
127.text: Do legislative committees hold public hearings on the individual budgets of central government administrative units (i.e., ministries, departments, and agencies) in which testimony from the executive branch is heard?

128.a: Yes, public hearings in which testimony from the public is heard are held on the budgets of a wide range of administrative units.
128.c: Yes, public hearings in which testimony from the public is heard are held on the budgets of a small number of administrative units.
128.b: Yes, public hearings in which testimony from the public is heard are held on the budgets of some administrative units.
128.d: No, public hearings in which testimony from the public is heard are not held on the budgets of administrative units.
128.text: Do legislative committees hold public hearings on the individual budgets of central government administrative units (i.e., ministries, departments, and agencies) in which testimony from the public is heard?

129.a: Yes, the committees release reports, which include all written and spoken testimony presented at the hearings.
129.c: Yes, the committees release reports, but they include only some testimony presented at the hearings.
129.b: Yes, the committees release reports, which include most testimony presented at the hearings.
129.d: No, the committees do not release reports, or do not hold public hearings.
129.text: Do the legislative committees that hold public hearings on the budget release reports to the public on these hearings?

130.a: Yes, the SAI maintains formal mechanisms through which the public can assist in formulating its audit program, and these mechanisms are accessible and widely used by the public.
130.c: Yes, the SAI maintains formal mechanisms through which the public can assist in formulating its audit program, but these mechanisms are not accessible.
130.b: Yes, the SAI maintains formal mechanisms through which the public can assist in formulating its audit program; while these mechanisms are accessible, they are not widely used by the public.
130.d: No, the SAI does not have formal mechanisms through which the public can assist in formulating its audit program.
130.text: Does the Supreme Audit Institution (SAI) maintain formal mechanisms through which the public can assist in formulating its audit program (by identifying the agencies, programs, or projects that should be audited)?

131.a: Yes, the SAI maintains formal mechanisms through which the public can participate in audit investigations, and these mechanisms are accessible and widely used by the public.
131.c: Yes, the SAI maintains formal mechanisms through which the public can participate in audit investigations, but these mechanisms are not accessible.
131.b: Yes, the SAI maintains formal mechanisms through which the public can participate in audit investigations; while these mechanisms are accessible, they are not widely used by the public.
131.d: No, the SAI does not have formal mechanisms through which the public can participate in audit investigations.
131.text: Does the Supreme Audit Institution (SAI) maintain formal mechanisms through which the public can participate in audit investigations (as respondents, witnesses, etc.)?

132.a: Yes, in addition to publishing Audit Reports, the SAI maintains other mechanisms of communication to make the public aware of audit findings (such as maintaining an office that regularly conducts outreach activities to publicize previously released audit findings).
132.b: No, the SAI does not maintain any formal mechanisms of communication with the public beyond publishing Audit Reports.
132.text: Does the Supreme Audit Institution (SAI) maintain any communication with the public regarding its Audit Reports beyond simply making these reports publicly available?

133.a: Yes, the SAI issues reports on the inputs it received from the public and provides detailed feedback on how these inputs have been used.
133.c: Yes, the SAI issues reports on the inputs it received from the public but provides no feedback on how these inputs have been used.
133.b: Yes, the SAI issues reports on the inputs it received from the public but provides only limited feedback on how these inputs have been used.
133.d: No, the SAI does not issue reports on the inputs it received from the public through public consultations.
133.text: Does the Supreme Audit Institution (SAI) provide formal, detailed feedback to the public on how their inputs have been used to determine its audit program or in Audit Reports?

134.a: At least four months in advance of the budget year, and at least one month before the executive’s budget proposal is introduced in the legislature
134.c: Less than two months in advance of the budget year, but at least one month before the executive’s budget proposal is introduced in the legislature
134.b: At least two months, but less than four months, in advance of the budget year, and at least one month before the executive’s budget proposal is introduced in the legislature
134.d: Does not release to the public, or is released less than one month before the executive’s budget proposal is introduced to the legislature
134.text: When is the Pre-Budget Statement made available to the public?

135.a: At least three months in advance of the budget year, and in advance of the budget being approved by the legislature
135.c: Less than two months in advance of the budget year, but at least in advance of the budget being approved by the legislature
135.b: At least two months, but less than three months, in advance of the budget year, and in advance of the budget being approved by the legislature
135.d: Does not release to the public, or is released after the budget has been approved by the legislature
135.text: When is the Executive Budget Proposal made available to the public?

136.a: Two weeks or less after the budget has been enacted
136.c: More than six weeks, but less than three months, after the budget has been enacted
136.b: Between two weeks and six weeks after the budget has been enacted
136.d: Does not release to the public, or is released more than three months after the budget has been enacted
136.text: When is the Enacted Budget made available to the public?

137.a: At least every month, and within one month of the period covered
137.c: At least semi-annually, and within three months of the period covered
137.b: At least every quarter, and within three months of the period covered
137.d: Does not release to the public
137.text: When are In-Year Reports made available to the public?

138.a: Six weeks or less after the mid-point
138.c: More than nine weeks, but less than three months, after the mid-point
138.b: Nine weeks or less, but more than six weeks, after the mid-point
138.d: Does not release to the public, or is released more than three months after the mid-point
138.text: How long after the mid-point in the fiscal year (i.e., six months into the fiscal year) is the Mid-Year Review made available to the public?

139.a: Six months or less after the end of the budget year
139.c: More than nine months, but within 12 months, after the end of the budget year
139.b: Nine months or less, but more than six months, after the end of the budget year
139.d: Does not release to the public, or is released more than 12 months after the end of the budget year
139.text: How long after the end of the budget year is the Year-End Report made available to the public?

140.a: Six months or less after the end of the budget year
140.c: More than 12 months, but within 18 months, after the end of the budget year
140.b: 12 months or less, but more than six months, after the end of the budget year
140.d: Does not release to the public, or is released more than 18 months after the end of the budget year
140.text: How long after the end of the fiscal year are the final annual expenditures of national departments audited and released (except for secret programs)?
